Events*   8 ;ndash; Roman Empire general Tiberius defeats the Dalmatae on the river Bathinus.* 435 ;ndash; Deposed Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople Nestorius, considered the originator of Nestorianism, is exiled by Roman Emperor Theodosius II to a monastery in Egypt.* 881 ;ndash; Battle of Saucourt-en-Vimeu: Louis III of France defeats the Vikings, an event celebrated in the poem ''Ludwigslied''.*1031 ;ndash; Olaf II of Norway is canonized as Saint Olaf by Grimketel, the English Bishop of Selsey.*1342 ;ndash; The Siege of Algeciras (1342–44)|Siege of Algeciras commences during the Spanish Reconquista.*1492 ;ndash; Christopher Columbus sets sail from Palos de la Frontera, Spain.*1527 ;ndash; The first known letter from North America is sent by John Rut while at St. John's, Newfoundland.*1601 ;ndash; Long War: Austria captures Transylvania in the Battle of Goroszló.*1645 ;ndash; Thirty Years' War: The Battle of Nördlingen (1645)|Second Battle of Nördlingen sees French forces defeating those of the Holy Roman Empire.*1678 ;ndash; René-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle|Robert LaSalle builds the ''Le Griffon'', the first known ship built on the Great Lakes.*1778 ;ndash; The theatre ''La Scala'' is inaugurated.*1795 ;ndash; Treaty of Greenville is signed.*1811 ;ndash; First ascent of Jungfrau, third highest summit in the Bernese Alps by brothers Johann Rudolf and Hieronymus Meyer.*1852 ;ndash; Harvard University wins the first Harvard–Yale Regatta|Boat Race between Yale University and Harvard. The race is also the first American intercollegiate athletic event*1860 ;ndash; The Second Maori War begins in New Zealand.*1900 ;ndash; The Firestone Tire and Rubber Company is founded.*1903 ;ndash; Macedonian rebels in Kruševo proclaim the Kruševo Republic, which exists only for ten days before Ottoman Turks lay waste to the town.*1907 ;ndash; Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis fines Standard Oil of Indiana a record $29.4 million for illegal rebating to freight carriers; the conviction and fine are later reversed on appeal.*1913 ;ndash; A major labour dispute, known as the Wheatland hop riot, starts in Wheatland, California.*1914 ;ndash; World War I: Germany declares war against France.*1921 ;ndash; Major League Baseball Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis confirms the ban of the eight Chicago Black Sox, the day after they were acquitted by a Chicago court.*1929 ;ndash; Jiddu Krishnamurti, tagged as the messianic "World Teacher", shocks the Theosophy movement by dissolving the Order of the Star, the organisation built to support him.*1936 ;ndash; Jesse Owens wins the 100 meter dash, defeating Ralph Metcalfe, at the Berlin Olympics.*  1936   ;ndash; A fire wipes out Kursha-2 in the Meshchera Lowlands, Ryazan Oblast, Russia, killing 1,200 and leaving only 20 survivors.*1940 ;ndash; World War II: Italian forces begin the invasion of British Somaliland.*1946 ;ndash; Holiday World ; Splashin' Safari|Santa Claus Land, the world's first themed amusement park, opens in Santa Claus, Indiana, United States.*1948 ;ndash; Whittaker Chambers accuses Alger Hiss of being a communist and a spy for the Soviet Union.*1958 ;ndash; The nuclear submarine 6 travels beneath the Arctic ice cap.*1959 ;ndash; Portugal's state police force PIDE fires upon striking workers in Bissau, Portuguese Guinea, killing over 50 people.*1960 ;ndash; Niger gains independence from France.*1961 ;ndash; The New Democratic Party of Canada is founded by the merger of the Co-operative Commonwealth Federation and the Canadian Labour Congress.*1972 ;ndash; The United States Senate ratifies the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.*1975 ;ndash; A privately chartered Boeing 707 strikes a mountain peak and crashes near Agadir, Morocco, killing 188.*1977 ;ndash; The United States Senate begins its hearing on Project MKUltra.*  1977   ;ndash; Tandy Corporation announces the TRS-80, one of the world's first mass-produced personal computers.*1981 ;ndash; Senegalese opposition parties, under the leadership of Mamadou Dia, launch the Antiimperialist Action Front – Suxxali Reew Mi.*1997 ;ndash; Oued El-Had and Mezouara massacre in Algeria; a total of 116 villagers killed, 40 in Oued El-Had and 76 in Mezouara.*2001 ;ndash; The Real IRA detonates a car bomb in Ealing, London, England, United Kingdom injuring seven people.*2004 ;ndash; The pedestal of the Statue of Liberty reopens after being closed since the September 11 attacks.*2005 ;ndash; President of Mauritania Maaouya Ould Sid'Ahmed Taya is overthrown in a Coup d'état|military coup while attending the funeral of King Fahd in Saudi Arabia.*  2005   ;ndash; Mahmoud Ahmadinejad becomes President of Iran.*2007 ;ndash; Former Deputy Director of the Dirección de Inteligencia Nacional|Chilean secret police Raúl Iturriaga is captured after having been on the run following a conviction for kidnapping.*2010 ;ndash; Widespread rioting erupts in Karachi, Pakistan, after the assassination of a local politician, leaving at least 85 dead and at least 17 billion Pakistani rupees (United States dollar|US$200 million) in damage.*2014 ;ndash; A 6.1 magnitude earthquake kills at least 617 people and injures more than 2,400 in Yunnan, China.Births*1491 ;ndash; Maria of Jülich-Berg (d. 1543)*1509 ;ndash; Étienne Dolet, French scholar and translator (d. 1546)*1692 ;ndash; John Henley, English minister and poet (d. 1759)*1734 ;ndash; Naungdawgyi, Burmese king (d. 1763)*1770 ;ndash; Frederick William III of Prussia (d. 1840)*1803 ;ndash; Joseph Paxton, English gardener and architect, designed The Crystal Palace (d. 1865)*1808 ;ndash; Hamilton Fish, American lawyer and politician, 26th United States Secretary of State (d. 1893)*1811 ;ndash; Elisha Otis, American businessman, founded the Otis Elevator Company (d. 1861)*1817 ;ndash; Archduke Albrecht, Duke of Teschen (d. 1895)*1832 ;ndash; Ivan Zajc, Croatian composer, conductor, and director (d. 1914)*1840 ;ndash; John Bigham, 1st Viscount Mersey, English jurist and politician (d. 1929